member.name: E:C1.WPF.Word.C1WordDocument.DrawingElement
member.summary: Occurs when the is about to render a .

remarks.para: This event fires once for each rendered after calls to the method. The event allows you to override the built-in rendering behavior and to render custom content for specific elements.
If you handle this event, then remember to set the property to true so the control will not render the element over your custom content.

example.para: The example below shows how you can use the event to provide custom rendering for elements of type 'RichTextBox'. The code checks the type of element being rendered. If the element is a 'RichTextBox', the code creates a to represent the object, then renders the image into the PDF document.
This example is quite general. You can use it to render any elements that do not expose their child elements as primitives such as , , rectangle, etc.
The drawback associated with rendering elements as images is that the output will contain raster images, which can be quite large and may look rough when you zoom in on the PDF.
